{
  "text": "Decreased humoral immunity may not only result from changes in B cells, but in part be caused by a disturbance of T cell help and alterations of cytokine levels, because many cytokines that control B cell functions are affected by aging [90, [CITATION_1] . As summarized in figure 3, a disturbed humoral response may be the result of a combination of an impaired interaction between antigen presenting cells (APC) and T helper cells and a shift in the TH1/TH2 balance, which both add to the immunological alterations that occur directly in B cells. It is noteworthy that zinc can antagonize all these effects: Zinc supplementation can suppress the release of pro-inflammatory cytokines from LPS-stimulated monocytes [CITATION_2] , and addition of zinc to PBMC promotes IFN-γ release [CITATION_3] . In vitro zinc supplementation can also decrease IL-10 release [CITATION_4] and restore IFN-α production from leukocytes of elderly subjects [CITATION_5] . However, the effect of zinc is not limited to cytokine expression, because the antiviral activity of IFN-α, but not IFN-β and -γ, is potentiated by addition of zinc in vitro [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
